  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "sgraffito",
                  "label": "Sgraffito"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Sgraffito"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is Italian for 'scratched' and it describes a layered drawing technique. A coat of white "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "slip",
                  "label": "slip"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "slip"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is painted onto a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "leather-hard",
                  "label": "leather-hard"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "leather-hard"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " clay "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "slab",
                  "label": "slab"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "slab"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tile. Once the slip has stiffened slightly (still leather-hard itself), lines are scratched through it with a needle tool to reveal the terracotta or grey clay body beneath, drawing a simple landscape of hills, trees, and a horizon line. The contrast between the white and clay colour creates a graphic, print-like image. No kiln needed, though the approach is slightly more demanding than the other beginner projects in this series."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
