      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Preparation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sketch your landscape design on paper first at the tile's dimensions. Keep it simple: a horizon line, 2-3 rolling hills, and a tree or two. Sgraffito works best with bold outlines rather than fine detail."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Roll the clay using 8 mm guide sticks to produce a tile 8 mm thick. Cut to your chosen tile size (15 x 20 cm is a good working size) using the fettling knife."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Allow the tile to dry uncovered on flat baking paper until it reaches "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "leather-hard",
                          "label": "leather-hard"
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "leather-hard"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " stage. This takes 3-5 hours depending on room temperature. The tile should feel firm and cool but not pale right through."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Applying the slip"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Stir the white "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "slip",
                          "label": "slip"
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "slip"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " until it is an even, creamy consistency. Apply a generous, even coat over the entire tile surface using the hake brush. Work in parallel strokes and avoid going back over wet slip or it will drag."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Apply a second coat once the first is no longer shiny (about 20-30 minutes). Two coats give enough opacity for a clear contrast."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Allow the slip to stiffen until it is no longer tacky when you lightly touch it with a fingertip. This is the right window for sgraffito carving: soft enough to cut cleanly but stiff enough not to smear. This typically takes 30-60 minutes after the second coat."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scratching back the landscape"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Working from your paper sketch, use the needle tool to scratch the horizon line first -- a single curved or gently undulating line across the tile. Press firmly enough to cut through both coats of "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "slip",
                          "label": "slip"
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "slip"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " and just into the clay surface below."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Add the hill curves above the horizon, then tree trunks, branch structures, and any ground detail below. Use the tip of the needle tool for thin lines and the side of the shaft for wider scraped marks."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Blow away or brush away the loose slip crumbs as you work. Do not wipe with a damp cloth as this will smear the design."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "To remove large areas of slip (for a white sky, for example), hold the needle tool nearly flat and push it sideways across the surface. This uncovers broad areas of clay for strong contrast with the "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "sgraffito",
                          "label": "sgraffito"
                        }
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "sgraffito"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " line work."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Drying and sealing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave the tile flat on baking paper to dry fully. Cover loosely for the first 12 hours to slow drying. Allow 3 days for an 8 mm tile."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Apply two coats of diluted PVA (1:1 with water) with the mop brush, allowing 1 hour between coats. The PVA seals both the slip surface and the exposed clay in the scratched lines."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Mount on the wall using picture pads or a simple picture hook through a pre-pierced hole. Pierce the hole before the slip coat if possible."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Variations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use black slip over a white or buff clay body for an inverted palette."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Scratch a botanical illustration -- a single stem with leaves -- for a more focused design."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Apply two different slip colours in bands (blue sky, white horizon, green ground) and scratch back through all layers for a multi-tone effect."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Make a diptych: two tiles side by side showing a panoramic landscape that spans both."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "problem": "The slip peeled or flaked off the tile when scratching",
              "cause": "Slip was applied to bone-dry clay or the tile had dried past leather-hard before the slip went on",
              "fix": "Slip bonds best to leather-hard clay. Lightly mist the tile surface with water before applying slip if it has dried past that stage."
            },
            {
              "problem": "Lines smeared rather than scratching cleanly",
              "cause": "The slip was still too wet when scratching began",
              "fix": "Wait until the slip surface is no longer shiny and does not feel tacky before starting the sgraffito stage."
            },
            {
              "problem": "The slip cracked in a fine network pattern",
              "cause": "Slip was applied too thickly in one heavy coat",
              "fix": "Apply two thinner coats rather than one thick one. If crazing is decorative you can leave it; seal well so it does not flake."
            },
            {
              "problem": "Scratched lines are ragged with rough edges",
              "cause": "Slip was applied too thickly and the edges lifted on cutting",
              "fix": "Blow away loose crumbs immediately after each stroke. Thin coats and sharp strokes produce cleaner lines."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
